TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bhattacharya, Utpal
AU  - Daouk, Hazem
T1  - When No Law is Better Than a Good Law*
PY  - 2009
Y1  - 2009/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfp011
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 13
IS  - 4
SP  - 577
EP  - 627
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - This paper argues, both theoretically and empirically, that sometimes no securities law may be better than a good securities law that is not enforced. The first part of the paper formalizes the sufficient conditions under which this happens for any law. The second part of the paper shows that a specific securities law – the law prohibiting insider trading – may satisfy these conditions. The third part of the paper takes this prediction to the data. We find that the cost of equity actually rises when some countries enact an insider trading law, but do not enforce it.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfp011
ER  - 



